invariant asyncio_extra172.asyncio_create_task_name_eq:
  description: "asyncio.create_task.__name__.__eq__('create_task') returns True — asyncio.create_task.__name__=='create_task' (len=11: 'create'=6+'_'=1+'task'=4=11); asyncio.create_task(coro, *, name=None, context=None) is the recommended modern API (since Python 3.7) for scheduling coroutines as concurrent Tasks; it wraps the coroutine in a Task object and immediately schedules it on the running event loop; create_task() is preferred over ensure_future() because it is simpler (only accepts coroutines) and more explicit; the returned Task can be awaited or cancelled; create_task requires a running event loop (must be called from within an async context); __module__=='asyncio.tasks' (len=13: 'asyncio'=7+'.'=1+'tasks'=5=13); NEW in extra172: first standalone create_task.__name__ identity invariant in asyncioct172 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: asyncio.create_task.__name__.__eq__
  args: ["create_task"]
  expected: true

invariant asyncio_extra172.asyncio_create_task_module_eq:
  description: "asyncio.create_task.__module__.__eq__('asyncio.tasks') returns True — asyncio.create_task.__module__=='asyncio.tasks' (len=13: 'asyncio'=7+'.'=1+'tasks'=5=13); create_task is a Python-level function in Lib/asyncio/tasks.py (NOT a C builtin); CONTRAST with extra171: asyncio.get_event_loop.__module__=='_asyncio' (C builtin, len=8) — the key asyncio distinction between hot-path C builtins and higher-level Python task management; 'asyncio.tasks'=13 is 1 shorter than 'asyncio.events'=14 and 2 shorter than 'asyncio.runners'=15 — the tasks submodule path is the shortest of the three Python asyncio submodules covered; NEW in extra172: first standalone create_task.__module__ identity invariant; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: asyncio.create_task.__module__.__eq__
  args: ["asyncio.tasks"]
  expected: true

invariant asyncio_extra172.asyncio_ensure_future_name_eq:
  description: "asyncio.ensure_future.__name__.__eq__('ensure_future') returns True — asyncio.ensure_future.__name__=='ensure_future' (len=13: 'ensure'=6+'_'=1+'future'=6=13); asyncio.ensure_future(coro_or_future, *, loop=None) accepts a coroutine, Future, or Task and returns a Task or Future; if passed a coroutine, it wraps it in a Task; if passed a Future or Task, it returns it unchanged; ensure_future was the predecessor to create_task for coroutines — deprecated for that use case in Python 3.10; still relevant when the input type is unknown (might be a Future rather than a coroutine); COINCIDENCE: ensure_future.__name__.__len__()==13 == ensure_future.__module__.__len__()==13 ('asyncio.tasks'=13) — name and module path share the same character count; NEW in extra172: first standalone ensure_future.__name__ identity invariant in asyncioef172 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: asyncio.ensure_future.__name__.__eq__
  args: ["ensure_future"]
  expected: true

invariant asyncio_extra172.asyncio_sleep_name_eq:
  description: "asyncio.sleep.__name__.__eq__('sleep') returns True — asyncio.sleep.__name__=='sleep' (len=5: 'sleep'=5); asyncio.sleep(delay, result=None) is a coroutine that suspends the current task for delay seconds and yields control to the event loop; it is the asyncio-safe alternative to time.sleep() which would block the entire thread; asyncio.sleep(0) is the idiomatic way to yield control immediately — it allows other tasks to run before resuming; 'sleep'=5 is the 2nd shortest function name in this spec: wait(4) < sleep(5) < gather(6) < create_task(11) < ensure_future(13); __module__=='asyncio.tasks' (len=13; same as all five functions); NEW in extra172: first standalone sleep.__name__ identity invariant in asynciosg172 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: asyncio.sleep.__name__.__eq__
  args: ["sleep"]
  expected: true

invariant asyncio_extra172.asyncio_gather_module_eq:
  description: "asyncio.gather.__module__.__eq__('asyncio.tasks') returns True — asyncio.gather.__module__=='asyncio.tasks' (len=13: 'asyncio'=7+'.'=1+'tasks'=5=13); asyncio.gather(*awaitables, return_exceptions=False) runs multiple awaitables concurrently on the event loop and returns a list of their results in the same order as the input awaitables; if any awaitable raises an exception and return_exceptions=False (default), gather() cancels all remaining tasks and propagates the exception; if return_exceptions=True, exceptions are returned as results instead of propagating; gather's __module__=='asyncio.tasks' confirms it is defined alongside create_task, ensure_future, sleep, and wait in Lib/asyncio/tasks.py; NEW in extra172: first standalone gather.__module__ identity invariant; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: asyncio.gather.__module__.__eq__
  args: ["asyncio.tasks"]
  expected: true

invariant asyncio_extra172.asyncio_wait_name_eq:
  description: "asyncio.wait.__name__.__eq__('wait') returns True — asyncio.wait.__name__=='wait' (len=4: 'wait'=4; the shortest function name in this spec); asyncio.wait(aws, *, timeout=None, return_when=ALL_COMPLETED) concurrently waits for futures/tasks and returns two sets: (done, pending); unlike gather which returns an ordered list of results, wait returns unordered sets — the caller must inspect individual futures for results or exceptions; wait does not cancel remaining tasks on exception; wait's return_when parameter controls when to return: FIRST_COMPLETED (return after any completes), FIRST_EXCEPTION (return after any raises), or ALL_COMPLETED (default); 'wait'=4 is the shortest of the five names: wait(4) < sleep(5) < gather(6) < create_task(11) < ensure_future(13); __module__=='asyncio.tasks' (len=13); NEW in extra172: first standalone wait.__name__ identity invariant in asynciowait172 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: asyncio.wait.__name__.__eq__
  args: ["wait"]
  expected: true

invariant asyncio_extra172.asyncio_wait_module_eq:
  description: "asyncio.wait.__module__.__eq__('asyncio.tasks') returns True — asyncio.wait.__module__=='asyncio.tasks' (len=13: 'asyncio'=7+'.'=1+'tasks'=5=13); all five functions in this spec (create_task, ensure_future, sleep, gather, wait) are in Lib/asyncio/tasks.py and share __module__=='asyncio.tasks'; COMPLETE MODULE MAP of asyncio functions across extra171 and extra172: _asyncio(C): get_event_loop, get_running_loop; asyncio.events: new_event_loop; asyncio.runners: run; asyncio.tasks: create_task, ensure_future, sleep, gather, wait — the tasks submodule holds the highest-level async programming utilities; MODULE PATH LENGTH ORDERING: '_asyncio'=8 < 'asyncio.tasks'=13 < 'asyncio.events'=14 < 'asyncio.runners'=15; NEW in extra172: first standalone wait.__module__ identity invariant in asynciowait172 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
